Section 8 — Pay-Per-Minute Reading System
Complete Production Specification for App Store Publishing
🚨  THIS IS THE CORE REVENUE FEATURE OF THE ENTIRE PLATFORM. Every subsection of Section 8 is mandatory. Nothing here is optional. Nothing here is a suggestion. The reading system must be fully functional, billing-accurate, App Store compliant, and capable of handling real money from real users on day one of public launch. If any part of this section is incomplete, the app cannot be published and cannot earn revenue.

8.0 What This System Must Do
The pay-per-minute reading system is the entire reason SoulSeer exists. It must do the following without failure, without exception, and without approximation:
•	Connect a paying client with a SoulSeer reader in real time via text chat, voice call, or video call
•	Bill the client accurately — to the minute — for the exact time both parties are connected, at the reader's stated per-minute rate
•	Protect the client from being overcharged — never bill for time when the session was not actually live
•	Protect the reader's earnings — ensure every minute they work is recorded and compensated
•	Handle network interruptions gracefully — a dropped connection is not the same as ending a session
•	Complete every session with a clean financial record — duration, cost, payment status, and transcript all saved
•	Function identically on iOS, Android, and web browsers — all three platforms must work for App Store and Google Play submission
🚨  Billing must be 100% server-side. The client device NEVER reports how long a session lasted, how much to charge, or how much the reader earned. The server owns all of this. A client who manipulates their app, kills the process, or tampers with API calls must not be able to steal a reading or avoid being billed for time they used.

8.1 Agora Architecture — What Gets Used and Why
SoulSeer uses two separate Agora products simultaneously for voice and video readings, and one Agora product for chat readings. Understanding the distinction is critical before writing a single line of Agora code.
Agora Product	Used For	What It Does
Agora RTC SDK	Voice readings, Video readings	Real-time audio and video transmission between two users
Agora RTM SDK	Chat readings, Signaling for ALL reading types	Real-time text messaging and presence/signaling channel
Agora RTM (Signaling)	Session coordination for voice and video	Used to send session control messages: ready, end call, mute status, grace period notices

⚠️  For voice and video readings, BOTH RTC and RTM are active at the same time. RTC carries the audio/video. RTM carries the control signals. Do not try to send control messages through the RTC data channel.
8.1.1 Agora App ID and Token Security
🚨  The Agora App ID and App Certificate must NEVER appear in client-side code, environment variables exposed to the browser, or any file that gets bundled into the app. They live only on the server. The client receives only short-lived tokens.
•	AGORA_APP_ID — stored in server .env only
•	AGORA_APP_CERTIFICATE — stored in server .env only. Required to generate tokens.
•	Client receives a dynamically generated, short-lived token per session from your server
•	Token is scoped to a specific channel name and a specific user UID
•	Token expires after 3600 seconds (1 hour) — sufficient for any session
•	If a token expires mid-session, the client silently renews it via the token refresh endpoint without interrupting the session
8.1.2 Agora User UIDs
•	Use the internal database user ID (integer) as the Agora UID for all sessions
•	This ensures the server can always match an Agora UID to a database user without maintaining a separate mapping
8.1.3 Agora Channel Naming
•	Every reading session gets a unique Agora channel name — format: reading_[readingId] (e.g., reading_4821)
•	This same channel name is used for both RTC and RTM
•	The server generates this name when the reading record is created and stores it in the readings table

8.2 Token Server — Server-Side Token Generation
🚨  Token generation happens on your server using the agora-token npm package. Never use a third-party token server. Never generate tokens on the client.
8.2.1 Required Package
npm install agora-token
8.2.2 Token Types
Token Type	Agora Function	Used For
RTC Token	RtcTokenBuilder.buildTokenWithUid()	Voice and video sessions — joining the audio/video channel
RTM Token	RtmTokenBuilder.buildToken()	Chat sessions and signaling for all session types

8.2.3 Token Endpoint
•	Route: POST /api/readings/:id/agora-token
•	Auth: Authenticated — only the reading's clientId or readerId may call this
•	Server verifies the reading exists, is in 'accepted' or 'in_progress' status, and the requesting user is a participant
•	Returns: { rtcToken, rtmToken, channelName, uid, appId }
•	Both the client and the reader call this endpoint before attempting to join the Agora channel
•	Token refresh: same endpoint called again with refresh=true query param to silently renew an expiring token

8.3 Complete Reading Lifecycle — Every Step, In Order
🚨  Every state transition in this lifecycle must be recorded in the readings table. If the server restarts, crashes, or loses memory, the database must contain enough information to understand what happened to every reading and what billing occurred.
8.3.1 Reading Status State Machine
Status	Meaning	Next Valid Statuses
pending	Client requested, waiting for reader to accept	accepted, cancelled
accepted	Reader accepted, both users fetching tokens	in_progress, cancelled
in_progress	Both joined Agora, billing timer running	completed, cancelled
completed	Session ended normally, billing finalized	(terminal)
cancelled	Session ended abnormally or never started	(terminal)

⚠️  Status transitions must only move forward. An 'in_progress' reading must never go back to 'pending'. A 'completed' reading must never be updated again. Validate status before every update.
8.3.2 Step-by-Step Lifecycle
Step 1 — Client Requests a Reading
•	Client selects a reader and reading type (chat, voice, or video) and clicks 'Start Reading'
•	Server checks: is reader online? (isOnline = true). If not, return 400 — do not create the reading
•	Server checks: does client have at least the cost of 5 minutes at this reader's rate? If not, redirect to Add Funds — do not create the reading
•	Server creates reading record with status = 'pending', stores readerId, clientId, type, pricePerMinute, channelName
•	Server sends a real-time notification to the reader via WebSocket: { type: 'new_reading_request', reading }
•	Client UI shows a waiting screen with a 60-second countdown — if reader does not accept in 60 seconds, server auto-cancels and notifies client
Step 2 — Reader Accepts
•	Reader clicks 'Accept' on the incoming request notification
•	Server updates reading status to 'accepted'
•	Server notifies both client and reader via WebSocket: { type: 'reading_accepted', readingId, channelName }
•	Both apps immediately call POST /api/readings/:id/agora-token to retrieve their tokens and initialize the Agora SDK
Step 3 — Both Join Agora
•	Client and reader both join the Agora channel using their respective tokens
•	When both have joined: each app calls POST /api/readings/:id/start
⚠️  POST /api/readings/:id/start is idempotent — if startedAt is already set, return 200 with no further action. Never start two billing timers for one reading.
•	Server sets status = 'in_progress', records startedAt, starts server-side billing timer
•	Server sends WebSocket message to both: { type: 'session_billing_started', readingId }
Step 4 — Active Session
•	Billing timer fires every 60 seconds on the server (see Section 8.5 for full billing logic)
•	Client UI shows: elapsed time counter, running cost counter, remaining balance
•	Server sends a balance update to the client via WebSocket after every billing tick
•	If client balance falls below the cost of 2 more minutes: server sends a low balance warning
Step 5 — Session Ends (Normal)
•	Either party clicks 'End Session'
•	App sends an RTM signal to the other participant: { type: 'session_ending', initiatedBy: userId }
•	Both apps call POST /api/readings/:id/end
•	Server stops billing timer, finalizes the reading record (status = 'completed', completedAt, duration, totalPrice, paymentStatus = 'paid')
•	Client is shown session summary screen and prompted to rate the reading
Step 6 — Session Ends (Abnormal)
See Section 8.6 for the full disconnection and grace period specification.

