8.5 Server-Side Billing — Complete Specification
🚨  This is the most security-critical code in the entire application. Errors here mean either clients are overcharged (chargebacks, refunds, App Store violations, potential legal liability) or readers are underpaid (breach of contractor agreement). Every line of billing code must be reviewed, tested, and treated as financial infrastructure.
8.5.1 Billing Timer Architecture
•	When POST /api/readings/:id/start is received, the server creates an in-memory billing session object and starts a setInterval timer firing every 60,000ms
•	In-memory sessions stored in a Map<readingId, BillingSession> — backed by the database after every tick
🚨  If the server restarts while sessions are in progress, the in-memory Map is lost. On server startup, query the DB for all readings with status = 'in_progress'. For each one, calculate elapsed minutes since startedAt, charge that amount, and set status to 'completed'. Do not leave orphaned in-progress readings after a restart.
8.5.2 Per-Minute Billing Tick — Exact Logic
This is exactly what must happen inside the setInterval callback, in this exact order:
1.	Fetch the current reading record from DB. If status is not 'in_progress', clear the timer and return — do not bill.
2.	Fetch the client user record from DB. Get their current accountBalance.
3.	Check: is accountBalance >= pricePerMinute? If NO: go to Section 8.5.3 (Insufficient Balance).
4.	If YES: begin a database transaction.
5.	Inside the transaction: deduct pricePerMinute from client's accountBalance.
6.	Inside the transaction: calculate readerShare = Math.floor(pricePerMinute * 0.70). Add readerShare to reader's accountBalance.
7.	Inside the transaction: increment billedMinutes on the reading record. Update duration = billedMinutes.
8.	Inside the transaction: insert a row into the transactions table — type: 'reading_charge', userId: clientId, amount: pricePerMinute, readingId, balanceBefore, balanceAfter.
9.	Commit the transaction. If commit fails, do NOT notify users and do NOT update in-memory state. Log the error. Retry once on the next tick.
10.	After successful commit: send WebSocket message to client: { type: 'billing_tick', billedMinutes, totalCharged, newBalance }
11.	Send WebSocket message to reader: { type: 'billing_tick', billedMinutes, totalEarned }
⚠️  Use Math.floor for the reader share — never floating point math for money. The platform always retains the rounding remainder.
8.5.3 Insufficient Balance During Session
12.	Immediately stop the billing timer — clearInterval.
13.	Do NOT charge the partial minute. The client is not billed for time they could not pay for.
14.	DB transaction: set reading status = 'completed', completedAt = now(), duration = billedMinutes, totalPrice = billedMinutes * pricePerMinute, paymentStatus = 'paid'.
15.	Send RTM signal to both participants: { type: 'session_ended', reason: 'insufficient_balance' }
16.	Send WebSocket message to client: { type: 'session_ended', reason: 'insufficient_balance', totalCharged, duration }
17.	Send WebSocket message to reader: { type: 'session_ended', reason: 'client_balance_exhausted', totalEarned, duration }
⚠️  Warn the client before this happens. When balance < 2 minutes remaining, send a low balance warning. When < 1 minute, send a final warning.
8.5.4 Anti-Fraud and Double-Charge Prevention
•	POST /api/readings/:id/start checks if there is already an active billing session for this readingId in the server Map — if yes, return 200 without creating a second timer
•	POST /api/readings/:id/start checks if reading status is already 'in_progress' or 'completed' — if yes, return 200
•	Every billing tick checks reading status from DB before charging — if not 'in_progress', skip and clear the timer
•	POST /api/readings/:id/end is idempotent — if reading is already 'completed', return 200 with no action
•	All balance operations wrapped in DB transactions — network failure mid-transaction rolls back automatically

8.6 Disconnection Handling & Grace Period
🚨  A user losing their connection is not the same as ending a session. Treating every disconnect as a session end would result in clients stranded mid-reading and readers losing income due to network hiccups.
8.6.1 Types of Disconnection
Scenario	Cause	Correct Handling
Intentional end	User clicks End Session	Immediate session end, finalize billing
Network blip	Brief packet loss, tunnel, elevator	Grace period — resume automatically
App backgrounded (iOS)	User switches apps or locks phone	Audio continues, grace period if video drops
App crash	App force-closed or killed by OS	Detected via Agora onUserOffline — start grace period
Device lost power	Battery died or device turned off	Same as app crash — grace period
Reader goes offline	Reader closes app or loses connection	Grace period — reader may reconnect within 2 minutes

8.6.2 Grace Period Specification
•	Grace period duration: 2 minutes (120 seconds)
•	Triggered when: Agora fires onUserOffline for either participant AND reading status is 'in_progress'
•	When grace period starts: pause billing timer (save the timerId for resumption)
•	Notify the still-connected participant: { type: 'participant_disconnected', disconnectedUserId, graceSeconds: 120 }
•	Reconnection: if the disconnected user rejoins within 2 minutes, they call POST /api/readings/:id/reconnect — server resumes the billing timer and sends { type: 'session_resumed' } to both
•	Grace period expires: stop billing timer permanently, set reading status = 'completed', duration = billedMinutes (grace period time is NOT billed), send { type: 'session_ended', reason: 'disconnection_timeout' } to both
⚠️  The grace period itself is not billed. Only minutes where both participants were actively connected are charged.
8.6.3 Detecting Disconnection
•	Agora RTC fires onUserOffline(uid, reason) when a remote user drops — client app reports this event to POST /api/readings/:id/participant-status
•	Heartbeat: both apps send a WebSocket ping every 30 seconds during an active session. If the server doesn't receive a ping for 90 seconds, treat it as a disconnect and start grace period

8.7 Reading System API Routes — Complete Reference
Method	Route	Auth	Purpose
POST	/api/readings/on-demand	Client	Create a new reading request. Validates reader online status and client minimum balance.
POST	/api/readings/:id/accept	Reader	Reader accepts the request. Notifies client. Updates status to 'accepted'.
POST	/api/readings/:id/reject	Reader	Reader declines. Updates status to 'cancelled'. Notifies client.
POST	/api/readings/:id/agora-token	Participant	Generate and return RTC + RTM tokens, channelName, uid, appId.
POST	/api/readings/:id/start	Participant	Mark both joined. Start server-side billing timer. Idempotent.
POST	/api/readings/:id/end	Participant	End session normally. Stop timer. Finalize billing. Idempotent.
POST	/api/readings/:id/reconnect	Participant	Resume session after disconnection within grace period.
POST	/api/readings/:id/participant-status	Participant	Report Agora onUserOffline event to server. Triggers grace period logic.
POST	/api/readings/:id/message	Participant	Store a chat message in the session transcript (chat readings only).
POST	/api/readings/:id/rate	Client	Submit star rating (1–5) and written review after session ends.
GET	/api/readings/:id	Participant	Get reading details including transcript (if chat).
GET	/api/readings/client	Client	Client's full reading history.
GET	/api/readings/reader	Reader	Reader's full session history.


